In article <Mar.5.18.18.57.1994.17944@romulus.rutgers.edu> wclark@romulus.rutgers.edu (Bill Clark) writes:
>kubo@bocher.harvard.edu (Tal Kubo) writes:
>
>>Similar pathologies can develop here. eg. NP-complete problem requires time
>>at least   C*2^n  for an unknowable value of C ---> not provably slower
>>than any particular polynomial.  Or: provably slower than any particular
>>polynomial, but no uniform proof that it's slower than *every* polynomial.

>I don't quite follow you here.  Is C a constant?  I assumed it was, but if
>so then its most certainly (eventually) larger than *every* (finite) 
>polynomial.  2^n, regardless of a coefficient, tends to grow faster than
>any polynomial function.  Did you mean something else?

He just meant that if C was an *unknowable* constant, that is, one
that could not be determined using ones favorite axiom systems, it
might be impossible to *prove* that the time required grew faster
than any polynomial, even though it actually *did* grow faster than every
one.







